We have looked at Rally and JIRA more closely and determined that rank does not always correspond to priority. Our current thinking is that we have three separate fields:

* String priority;
* PriortyLevel priorityLevel; // enum P1..P5
* float rank;

The user would have to choose to either sort by Priority or Rank. We'll need some more discussion how to handle the cases when containers are not homogeneous such as categories or the scheduled presentation. There is also a question what to do in Focus on Workweek mode which currently forces Priority ordering.

There are several use cases such as handling of selections in the task editor outline, opening of a particular attribute/comment in the editor from a hyperlink or highlighting of search matches that require an operation to select and reveal a model element in the task editor. Since the editor UI and task data model differs significantly between connectors the API needs to be extensible and flexible, e.g.:

 public class AbstractTaskEditorPage {

   public boolean selectAndReveal(IAdaptable element);

 }

I have commited a first cut of the generic XML-RPC layer in the new org.eclipse.mylyn.commons.xmlrpc plug-in. Frank, can you take a look and check if that works for Bugzilla?

XmlRpcClientTest and XmlRpcOperationTest have some sample code. The basic idea is that you create an instance of CommonXmlRpcClient and a subclass of XmlRpcOperation. The client holds the shared state between all calls and manages the transport (Apache XML-RPC). If needed you can customize the authentication, exception handling etc. by overriding protected methods in XmlRpcOperation. Let me know if you need additional hooks.

The client code should look something like this:

BugzillaXmlRpcClient {

  public BugzillaXmlRpcClient() {
    client = new CommonXmlRpcClient(repositoryLocation);
  }
  
  public voidDoSomething(final IProgressMonitor monitor) {
    	Integer response = (new BugzillaXmlRpcOperation<Integer>(client) {
			@Override
			public Integer execute() throws XmlRpcException {
			    Integer id = (Integer) call(monitor, "Bugzilla.createBug", "summary", "description");
				return call(monitor, "Bugzilla.doSomething", id);
			}
		}).execute();
    
  }
  
}

abstract BugzillaXmlRpcOperation extends XmlRpcOperation {

  protected boolean handleAuthenticationException(int code, AuthScheme authScheme) throws XmlRpcException {
    ... do something custom if needed ...
    super.handleAuthenticationException(code,authScheme);
  }
  
}

